{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651386"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:23:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:23:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18446"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60326"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7801"},{"type":"tags","id":"7802"},{"type":"tags","id":"7805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is planning a study to compare mean blood pressure between two groups. They want to ensure their study has adequate statistical power to detect a clinically meaningful difference between the groups.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between sample size and statistical power?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Power remains constant regardless of sample size","Power decreases as sample size increases","Power increases as sample size increases","Power is only affected by effect size","Power is only affected by significance level"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct relationship is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epower increases as sample size increases\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because larger sample sizes provide more precise estimates and greater ability to detect true differences between groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPower remains constant regardless of sample size\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EPower decreases as sample size increases \u003C/strong\u003E- Power is directly influenced by sample size as larger samples provide more statistical power.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPower is only affected by effect size or significance level\u003C/strong\u003E - While effect size and significance level (\u237a) do both influence power, they are not the only factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStatistical power is influenced by multiple factors including sample size, effect size, variability in the data, and significance level. Larger sample sizes allow detection of smaller effects while maintaining adequate power. This relationship is crucial for study planning to ensure meaningful results can be obtained.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Statistical power increases with larger sample sizes, larger effect sizes, and lower variability in the data.","To detect smaller effect sizes, larger sample sizes are needed to maintain adequate statistical power.","Power calculations help determine the minimum sample size needed to detect a specified effect size at a given significance level."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60326"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60326"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T13:25:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T13:30:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:30:29+10:30"},